1 A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
2 AN ACT TO ESTABLISH REQUIREMENTS FOR SITING AND OPERATION OF DATA
3 CENTERS AND TO MAKE VARIOUS CHANGES TO STATE ENERGY AND
4 UTILITIES POLICY.
5 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
6
7 PART I. REQUIREMENTS FOR DATA CENTERS
8
9 REQUIREMENTS FOR LOCAL DEVELOPMENT APPROVAL PROCESS
10 SECTION 1.(a) Article 9 of Chapter 160D of the General Statutes is amended by
11 adding a new section to read:
12 "§ 160D-974. Site assessment required for data centers; other requirements.
13 (a) Prior to any approval of a rezoning application, special exception, conditional or
14 special use permit, or building permit for the siting of a new data center, a local government shall
15 require that an applicant:
16 (1) Perform and submit a site assessment to examine the sound profile of the data
17 center on residential units and schools located within 500 feet of the data
18 center property boundary. A locality may also require that a site assessment
19 examine the effect of the proposed facility on the community with regard to
20 (i) ground and surface water resources, (ii) air quality, (iii) thermal plumes,
21 (iv) agricultural resources, (v) parks, (vi) registered historic sites, and (vii)
22 forestland on the data center site or immediately contiguous land.
23 (2) Submit an attestation that the data center will employ a closed-loop water or
24 a liquid cooling system that will result in minimization of water consumption
25 for cooling systems to the maximum extent possible, in compliance with
26 G.S. 143-355.5A.
27 (b) The site assessment submitted to a local government pursuant to subdivision (1) of
28 subsection (a) of this section shall be used by the local government to assess consistency with
29 the policies of the local government's comprehensive plan, if any, and compliance with the local
30 government's adopted noise ordinances, zoning ordinance provisions, and other applicable laws
31 and regulations, if any.
32 (c) This section shall not apply to a site with an existing legislative, quasi-judicial, or
33 administrative approval where an applicant is seeking an expansion or modification of an already
*S730-v-4*

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 existing or approved facility and such expansion does not exceed an additional monthly electrical
2 demand of 100 megawatts or more.
3 (d) For purposes of this section, the term "data center" means a facility, campus of
4 facilities, or array of interconnected facilities used by an entity or other business enterprise for
5 the primary purpose of storing, retrieving, managing, and processing digital data, which has a
6 peak monthly electricity demand of 100 megawatts or greater.
7 (e) Nothing in this section shall be construed to prohibit, limit, or otherwise supersede
8 existing local zoning authority."
9 SECTION 1.(b) This section is effective when it becomes law and applies to
10 applications for rezoning, special exceptions, conditional or special use permits, or building
11 permits submitted on or after that date.
12
13 CLOSED-LOOP WATER OR LIQUID COOLING SYSTEMS FOR DATA CENTERS
14 SECTION 2.(a) Article 38 of Chapter 143 of the General Statutes is amended by
15 adding a new section to read:
16 "§ 143-355.5A. Closed-loop water system required for data centers.
17 (a) A data center shall employ a closed-loop water or liquid cooling system that will
18 result in minimization of water consumption for cooling systems to the maximum extent possible.
19 (b) A data center may not employ evaporative or open-loop cooling systems.
20 (c) In accordance with G.S. 160D-974, the owner of a proposed data center must submit
21 a certification that the facility will employ a closed-loop water or liquid cooling system resulting
22 in a minimization of water consumption for cooling systems to the maximum extent possible, at
23 the time it applies for approval of a rezoning application, special exception, or special use permit
24 for the siting of the data center. In addition, the data center shall annually file a certification to
25 include third-party verification that the closed-loop cooling system remains operational, with
26 documentation of any water losses, chemical treatment processes, and fluid replacement
27 volumes.
28 (d) For purposes of this section, the following definitions apply:
29 (1) Closed-loop water or liquid cooling system. – A sealed cooling process in
30 which the same water or coolant circulates continuously with de minimis
31 withdrawal from or discharge into municipal systems, groundwater sources,
32 or surface waters.
33 (2) Data center. – A facility, campus of facilities, or array of interconnected
34 facilities used by an entity or other business enterprise for the primary purpose
35 of storing, retrieving, managing, and processing digital data, which has a peak
36 monthly electricity demand of 100 megawatts or greater."
37 SECTION 2.(b) This section is effective when it becomes law and applies to data
38 centers for which no local development approvals or State permits, certifications, or
39 authorizations have been issued for siting of the data center on or before that date.
40
41 PROHIBIT CERTAIN FOREIGN OWNERSHIP OF DATA CENTERS AND LAND
42 UPON WHICH DATA CENTERS ARE SITED
43 SECTION 3.(a) Chapter 64 of the General Statutes is amended by adding a new
44 Article to read:
45 "Article 5.
46 "Prohibit Adversarial Foreign Government Ownership of Data Centers and Land on which Data
47 Centers are Located.
48 "§ 64-64. Definitions.
49 As used in this Article, the following definitions apply:
50 (1) Adversarial nation. – One of the following:
51 a. China.
Page 2 Senate Bill 730-Fourth Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 b. Iran.
2 c. North Korea.
3 d. Russia.
4 (2) Data center. – A facility, campus of facilities, or array of interconnected
5 facilities used by an entity or other business enterprise for the primary purpose
6 of storing, retrieving, managing, and processing digital data, which has a peak
7 monthly electricity demand of 100 megawatts or greater.
8 (3) De minimis direct interest. – Any ownership of land or a data center resulting
9 from ownership of registered equities in a publicly traded company owning
10 the land or data center and if the ownership interest in the company is either
11 of the following:
12 a. Less than five percent (5%) of any class of registered equities.
13 Ownership of registered equities is determined by processes
14 established under federal law.
15 b. Less than five percent (5%) interest in an entity controlled by a
16 company that is both registered with the United States Securities and
17 Exchange Commission as an investment adviser under the Investment
18 Advisers Act of 1940, as amended, and is not a foreign entity.
19 (4) Foreign government. – Any government other than the federal government or
20 the government of a state or a political subdivision of a state.
21 (5) Interest. – Any estate, remainder, or reversion, or any portion of the estate,
22 remainder, or reversion, or an option pursuant to which one party has a right
23 to cause the transfer of legal or equitable title to land described in
24 G.S. 64-65(a), including, without limitation, a lease of land described in
25 G.S. 64-65(a) (i) for a term of one year or longer or (ii) renewable by option
26 for terms which, if the options were all exercised, would total one year or
27 longer.
28 (6) Party. – Any individual, corporation, company, association, firm, partnership,
29 society, joint-stock company, trust, estate, or any other legal entity.
30 (7) Prohibited foreign party. – Any of the following:
31 a. A citizen or resident of an adversarial nation.
32 b. A foreign government formed within an adversarial nation.
33 c. A party other than an individual or government that is created or
34 organized under the laws of a foreign government within an
35 adversarial nation.
36 d. A party other than an individual or a government that meets all of the
37 following criteria:
38 1. Is created or organized under the laws of any state.
39 2. A significant interest or substantial control is directly or
40 indirectly held or is capable of being exercised by one or more
41 of the following:
42 I. An individual referred to in sub-subdivision a. of this
43 subdivision.
44 II. A foreign government referred to in sub-subdivision b.
45 of this subdivision.
46 III. A party referred to in sub-subdivision c. of this
47 subdivision.
48 IV. A combination of the individuals, parties, or
49 governments referred to in this sub-sub-subdivision.
50 e. An agent, trustee, or other fiduciary of a person or entity enumerated
51 in this subdivision.
