16 REQUIREMENTS FOR UTILITY SERVICE CONTRACTS WITH DATA CENTERS
17 SECTION 4.(a) Article 7 of Chapter 62 of the General Statutes is amended by adding
18 a new section to read:
19 "§ 62-142.1. Contracts with data centers.
20 (a) Each data center located in North Carolina is required to enter into an electric service
21 contract with the electric public utility providing service to the data center. Each contract between
22 an electric public utility and a data center for the provision of electric service shall include terms
23 and conditions designed to (i) protect residential, other retail, and wholesale electricity customers
24 from costs incurred or reasonably anticipated to be incurred by the electric public utility to
25 provide electric service to the data center and (ii) prevent, to the maximum extent reasonably
26 feasible, other retail customers from subsidizing the cost of the data center's electric service. Such
27 contracts shall include all of the following:
28 (1) Minimum billing requirements designed to recover incremental costs
29 associated with serving or preparing to serve a data center.
30 (2) A contract term that is sufficient to recover all of the electric public utility's
31 incremental costs and which may exceed the length of the applicable service
32 tariff.
33 (3) Performance and credit provisions designed to protect retail customers in the
34 event of contract default.
35 (4) Termination provisions designed to protect retail customers in the event of
36 termination of the contract for electric service.
37 (b) Each contract between an electric public utility and a data center for the provision of
38 electric service shall be filed with the Commission as soon as practicable but in no event later
39 than 30 days from the date of contract execution by both parties. Either the utility or the data
40 center, or both, may designate all or any portion of a contract as confidential information as
41 defined in G.S. 132-1.2, or sensitive public security information as defined in G.S. 132-1.7.
42 Information shall be considered confidential only to the extent provided by law. Any dispute
43 about whether information has been properly designated as confidential shall be determined by
44 the Commission upon motion and response of interested parties. Subject to the requirements of
45 G.S. 62-34(c), the Public Staff shall have the right to examine confidential information, as well
46 as sensitive public security information, in exercising any power or performing any duty
47 authorized by this Chapter.
48 (c) As part of the report required on the long-range needs for the expansion of facilities
49 for the generation of electricity pursuant to G.S. 62-110.1(c), the electric public utility shall
50 include details on contracted demand versus actual demand for each data center for the previous
51 three years.
