8 RFP FOR STUDY OF UTILITY POLICIES TO INCREASE AFFORDABILITY OF
9 ELECTRIC RATES
10 SECTION 8. Recognizing the rising costs of utility service, the General Assembly
11 finds that an examination of various utility policies should be conducted to ensure these policies
12 are not exacerbating affordability issues for citizens of the State, including the 2050 goal for a
13 reduction in carbon dioxide (CO2) emitted in the State from electric generating facilities that
14 results in carbon neutrality, pursuant to G.S. 62-110.9. In addition to examining these existing
15 utility policies, the General Assembly finds that expert analysis should be performed to determine
16 the most effective approach to ensuring that costs of utility service to large load customers is not
17 borne by other residential, commercial, and industrial customers in North Carolina, including
18 appropriate terms for a large load tariff. The Legislative Services Officer shall issue a request for
19 proposals for a study to be conducted by an entity with nationally recognized expertise in research
20 and analysis of utility policy and rates to (i) ascertain the current impacts, and projected impacts
21 over the next 25 years, to residential, commercial, and industrial customer bills from the 2050
22 carbon neutrality goal, and whether any changes to this policy or other policies are advisable to
23 enhance customer affordability and (ii) provide recommendations for effective policies to prevent
24 rate impacts from large load customers on other customer classes, including requirements that
25 large load customers generate a portion of their own power, as well as curtailment policies for
26 large load customers. The study shall adhere to the following time line:
27 (1) The request for proposals (RFP) shall be issued on or before August 1, 2026.
28 (2) A contract to award the RFP shall be executed on or before November 1, 2026.
29 (3) The study shall be completed and submitted to the Joint Legislative
30 Commission on Energy Policy on or before May 1, 2027, in order to inform
31 the development of utility policy during the 2027 Regular Session.
32 The Utilities Commission and the Public Staff shall assist the (i) Legislative Services
33 Officer, as needed, in development of the RFP and the selection of a contractor and (ii) selected
34 contractor, in every permissible manner within the constraints of their respective authority, in the
35 conduct of the study.
36
37 EXPRESS PERMIT REVIEW FOR ENERGY PROJECTS
38 SECTION 9.(a) G.S. 143B-279.13 reads as rewritten:
39 "§ 143B-279.13. Express permit and certification reviews.
40 (a) The Department of Environmental Quality shall develop an express review program
41 to provide express permit and certification reviews in all of its regional offices. Participation in
42 the express review program is voluntary, and the program shall be supported by the fees
43 determined pursuant to subsection (b) of this section. The Department of Environmental Quality
44 shall determine the project applications to review under the express review program from those
45 who request to participate in the program. The express review program may be applied to any
46 one or all of the permits, approvals, or certifications in the following programs: the erosion and
47 sedimentation control program, the coastal management program, and the water quality
48 programs, including water quality certifications and stormwater management. The express
49 review program shall focus on the following permits or certifications:
50 (1) Stormwater permits under Part 1 of Article 21 of Chapter 143 of the General
51 Statutes.
Page 10 Senate Bill 730-Fourth Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (2) Stream origination certifications under Article 21 of Chapter 143 of the
2 General Statutes.
3 (3) Water quality certification under Article 21 of Chapter 143 of the General
4 Statutes.
5 (4) Erosion and sedimentation control permits under Article 4 of Chapter 113A
6 of the General Statutes.
7 (5) Permits under the Coastal Area Management Act (CAMA), Part 4 of Article
8 7 of Chapter 113A of the General Statutes.
9 (a1) The Department of Environmental Quality shall have the authority to create express
10 permitting options for programs in addition to those listed in subsection (a) of this section where
11 it deems there to be a need or where it determines an express permitting option would create
12 greater efficiencies for the permitting process.
13 (a2) The Department of Environmental Quality shall create an express review program for
14 all permits, authorizations, and certifications required from the Department for projects involving
15 the generation, distribution, or transmission of energy or fuel, including natural gas, diesel,
16 petroleum, or electricity. Participation in the express review program is voluntary.
17 (b) The Department of Environmental Quality shall set the fees for express application
18 review under the express review program at a level sufficient to cover all program expenses.
19 Notwithstanding G.S. 143-215.3D, the maximum permit application fee to be charged under
20 subsection (a) of this section for the express review of a project application requiring all of the
21 permits under subdivisions (1) through (5) of subsection (a) of this section shall not exceed five
22 thousand eight hundred eight dollars ($5,808). Notwithstanding G.S. 143-215.3D, the maximum
23 permit application fee to be charged for the express review of a project application requiring all
24 of the permits under subdivisions (1) through (4) of subsection (a) of this section shall not exceed
25 four thousand seven hundred fifty-two dollars ($4,752). Notwithstanding G.S. 143-215.3D, the
26 maximum permit application fee charged for the express review of a project application for any
27 other combination of permits under subdivisions (1) through (5) of subsection (a) of this section
28 shall not exceed four thousand two hundred twenty-four dollars ($4,224). As set forth in
29 subsection (a1) of this section, express review of a project application involving additional
30 permits or certifications issued by the Department of Environmental Quality other than those
31 under subdivisions (1) through (5) of subsection (a) of this section may be allowed by the
32 Department, and, notwithstanding G.S. 143-215.3D or any other statute or rule that sets a permit
33 fee, the maximum permit application fee charged for the express review of a project application
34 that includes a permit, approval, or certification designated for express review under subsection
35 (a1) of this section shall not exceed four thousand two hundred twenty-four dollars ($4,224), plus
36 one hundred fifty percent (150%) of the fee that would otherwise apply by statute or rule for that
37 particular permit, approval, or certification. Additional fees, not to exceed fifty percent (50%) of
38 the original permit application fee under this section, may be charged for subsequent reviews due
39 to the insufficiency of the permit applications. The Department of Environmental Quality may
40 establish the procedure by which the amount of the fees under this subsection is determined, and
41 the fees and procedures are not rules under G.S. 150B-2(8a) for the express review program
42 under this section."
43 SECTION 9.(b) G.S. 143B-279.20 reads as rewritten:
44 "§ 143B-279.20. Report on Department activity to process applications for permits
45 required for natural gas pipelines and gas-fired electric generation facilities.
46 The Department of Environmental Quality shall report on any applications received for
47 permits permits, authorizations, or certifications required for siting or operation of natural gas
48 pipelines and gas-fired electric generation facilities within the State, and activities of the
49 Department to process such applications, including tracking of processing times. The report shall
50 also include information on all activities under the express review program required pursuant to
51 G.S. 143B-279.13(a2). The processing time tracked shall include (i) the total processing time
Senate Bill 730-Fourth Edition Page 11

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 from when an initial permit application is received to issuance or denial of the permit and (ii) the
2 processing time from when a complete permit application is received to issuance or denial of the
3 permit. The Department shall report quarterly to the Joint Legislative Commission on Energy
4 Policy pursuant to this section."
5 SECTION 9.(c) Within 30 days of the date this section becomes law, the Department
6 shall notify applicants for all entities with pending applications for permits, authorizations, and
7 certifications required from the Department for projects involving the generation, distribution, or
8 transmission of energy or fuel, including natural gas, diesel, petroleum, or electricity, of the
9 express review program enacted by subsection (b) of this section, and shall inform the applicants
10 of the ability to process pending applications through the program upon payment of the applicable
11 fee pursuant to G.S. 143B-279.13(b).
12 SECTION 9.(d) This section is effective when it becomes law and applies to
13 applications for permits, authorizations, and certifications pending on or submitted after that date.
