15 REQUIRE DEVELOPMENT OF NUCLEAR RESOURCES PRIOR TO RETIREMENT
16 OF BASELOAD FACILITIES OR FACILITIES WITH DISPATCHABLE ELECTRIC
17 GENERATION ABOVE 100 MW TO ENSURE ADEQUACY OF GRID
18 SECTION 10. G.S. 62-110.9(4) reads as rewritten:
19 "(4) Retain discretion to determine optimal timing and generation and
20 resource-mix to achieve the least cost path to compliance with the authorized
21 carbon reduction goal, including discretion in achieving the authorized carbon
22 reduction goal by the date specified in order to allow for implementation of
23 solutions that would have a more significant and material impact on carbon
24 reduction; provided, however, the Commission shall not exceed the date
25 specified to achieve the authorized carbon reduction goal by more than two
26 years, except in the event the Commission authorizes construction of a nuclear
27 facility or wind energy facility that would require additional time for
28 completion due to technical, legal, logistical, or other factors beyond the
29 control of the electric public utility, or in the event necessary to maintain the
30 adequacy and reliability of the existing grid. In making such determinations,
31 the Utilities Commission shall receive and consider stakeholder input. The
32 Commission shall not authorize retirement of baseload facilities or facilities
33 with dispatchable electric generation above 100 MW until such time as a
34 certificate of public convenience and necessity has been issued to an electric
35 public utility for construction of one nuclear facility with a generating capacity
36 of at least 1,000 MW to ensure the adequacy of baseload and dispatchable
37 generation from a clean energy resource."
38
39 PART III. MISCELLANEOUS
40
41 COOLING-OFF PERIOD FOR UTILITIES COMMISSIONERS AND STAFF
42 SECTION 11.(a) Article 15 of Chapter 62 of the General Statutes is amended by
43 adding a new section to read:
44 "§ 62-327A. Post-employment restrictions on members and employees of Commission.
45 (a) Cooling-Off Period. ‒ It shall be unlawful for any former commissioner or employee
46 of the Commission to make, with the intent to influence on behalf of an employer or client, any
47 communication to or appearance before the Commission within a period of six months following
48 the termination of his or her service or employment with the Commission.
49 (b) Penalty. ‒ A violation of this section is a Class 3 misdemeanor."
50 SECTION 11.(b) This section becomes effective December 1, 2026, and applies to
51 offenses committed on or after that date.
